1
00:00:59,298 --> 00:01:00,698
What do you think
of Darren Jarvis?

2
00:01:00,858 --> 00:01:02,259
At CBS?

3
00:01:02,338 --> 00:01:03,692
He wants me to be
a correspondent.

4
00:01:03,778 --> 00:01:05,293
It's not
worth your time.

5
00:01:06,539 --> 00:01:08,179
What about Greer Fisher,
at MSNBC?

6
00:01:09,099 --> 00:01:11,774
Stick to writing,
do TV on the side.

7
00:01:11,858 --> 00:01:13,578
You're more than
a talking head.

8
00:01:15,340 --> 00:01:16,533
How about <i>Slugline?</i>

9
00:01:16,658 --> 00:01:17,855
What's <i>Slugline?</i>

10
00:01:18,378 --> 00:01:22,167
If I said <i>Politico</i> wanted to
hire me, what would you say?

11
00:01:22,259 --> 00:01:23,932
I would say that
that piques my interest.

12
00:01:24,099 --> 00:01:26,057
Six months from now,
<i>Slugline</i> will be

13
00:01:26,179 --> 00:01:28,137
what <i>Politico</i> was
a year and half ago.

14
00:01:28,298 --> 00:01:29,414
Everyone at <i>Politico</i>
reads it

15
00:01:29,500 --> 00:01:31,298
because <i>Slugline's</i> breaking
stories before they are.

16
00:01:31,378 --> 00:01:33,018
I wonder why I've
never heard of it.

17
00:01:33,099 --> 00:01:34,134
Everyone's
a free agent.

18
00:01:34,218 --> 00:01:36,733
And they write whatever they
want, wherever they are.

19
00:01:36,819 --> 00:01:38,378
Most people write
from their phones.

20
00:01:38,459 --> 00:01:41,453
Well, if freedom and exposure
are what they're offering,

21
00:01:41,578 --> 00:01:44,414
I would say that is
a meeting worth taking.

22
00:01:44,780 --> 00:01:47,215
This Hammerschmidt
thing is blowing up.

23
00:01:47,298 --> 00:01:49,176
I think he might
get fired.

24
00:01:49,259 --> 00:01:50,658
There's got to be
a thousand tweets here...

25
00:01:50,738 --> 00:01:53,173
People defending me,
people trashing me.

26
00:01:53,298 --> 00:01:55,608
There's even a hashtag,
GoZoe.

27
00:01:55,700 --> 00:01:56,688
Hmm.

28
00:01:59,738 --> 00:02:00,730
Hey!

29
00:02:01,658 --> 00:02:02,730
We mustn't leave
any trails.

30
00:02:02,858 --> 00:02:03,896
All of my contacts
were in there.

31
00:02:03,980 --> 00:02:07,417
Then it's time for you
to get some new contacts.

32
00:02:11,379 --> 00:02:13,530
Don't worry. I'll get you a phone.
I'll get you two, in fact.

33
00:02:13,618 --> 00:02:15,656
One for work
and a burner for play.

34
00:02:15,779 --> 00:02:17,498
Expect them
this afternoon.

35
00:02:20,099 --> 00:02:22,409
Oh, and... Go, Zoe.

36
00:04:34,699 --> 00:04:35,735
The reporter?

37
00:04:35,860 --> 00:04:36,896
Yes.

38
00:04:39,420 --> 00:04:40,934
Just this once?

39
00:04:44,819 --> 00:04:46,379
I'm not sure.

40
00:04:47,619 --> 00:04:49,531
What does she offer us?

41
00:04:50,778 --> 00:04:52,293
A mouthpiece,
when we need one.

42
00:04:52,379 --> 00:04:54,098
She's been
very useful so far.

43
00:04:54,459 --> 00:04:56,052
What does she want?
Access.

44
00:04:56,138 --> 00:04:58,016
A seat at the table.

45
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:00,170
Sounds like she's getting the
better side of the bargain.

46
00:05:01,379 --> 00:05:03,211
She can be controlled.

47
00:05:03,300 --> 00:05:04,778
Are you sure?

48
00:05:05,019 --> 00:05:06,295
She can.
I promise you.

49
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:09,412
Okay, if you say so.

50
00:05:10,420 --> 00:05:11,977
The moment you
want me to end it...

51
00:05:12,059 --> 00:05:13,812
I know, Francis.

52
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:18,939
I should get
ready for work.

53
00:05:32,939 --> 00:05:34,009
Hey...

54
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:36,410
I didn't think
you'd be in until later.

55
00:05:36,499 --> 00:05:38,138
This is your
agenda for the day.

56
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:39,939
Here's your schedule
for the rest of the week.

57
00:05:40,019 --> 00:05:42,057
These are papers that need
to be approved or signed.

58
00:05:42,138 --> 00:05:44,131
Over here are your one-sheets
for committee meetings

59
00:05:44,220 --> 00:05:47,257
and briefs on upcoming
legislative action.

60
00:05:47,338 --> 00:05:50,333
I filled Ashley in. She can cover
until you find a replacement.

61
00:05:59,220 --> 00:06:00,449
Christina.

62
00:06:01,660 --> 00:06:02,775
What?

63
00:06:06,379 --> 00:06:07,778
Thank you.

64
00:06:08,259 --> 00:06:10,819
For getting
all this in order.

65
00:06:15,660 --> 00:06:19,540
Ashley can call me if you have any
questions about what's on your desk.

66
00:06:24,138 --> 00:06:25,175
He here yet?

67
00:06:25,300 --> 00:06:26,336
I put him
in your office.

68
00:06:32,019 --> 00:06:34,898
Marty Spinella. Head lobbyist
for the teachers union.

69
00:06:34,980 --> 00:06:37,415
He wants to rip my head off
and peel it like an orange.

70
00:06:37,540 --> 00:06:40,293
Why? Because I lied to him.
But what choice did I have?

71
00:06:40,420 --> 00:06:43,891
When the truth would have ended
the conversation before it began?

72
00:06:43,980 --> 00:06:45,653
I'll call you back.
Marty.

73
00:06:47,660 --> 00:06:49,412
You fucking lied, Frank?

74
00:06:49,499 --> 00:06:51,492
No, no, no.
You lie to my fucking face?

75
00:06:51,619 --> 00:06:53,451
Marty, I did not lie. What
do you mean you did not?

76
00:06:53,540 --> 00:06:55,213
We spent a whole
weekend in that room

77
00:06:55,379 --> 00:06:57,052
poring over this bill
line by line.

78
00:06:57,138 --> 00:06:59,973
And nowhere did it say anything
about collective bargaining.

79
00:07:00,059 --> 00:07:02,973
Let's calm down and sit down.
And we will discuss this.

80
00:07:03,059 --> 00:07:06,257
I will explain everything that's
going on and we will talk it out.

81
00:07:06,379 --> 00:07:07,973
No matter how long it takes.
No. No more.

82
00:07:08,059 --> 00:07:09,540
This is gonna be
a very short meeting.

83
00:07:09,619 --> 00:07:11,771
'Cause only one of two
things are going to happen.

84
00:07:11,899 --> 00:07:14,891
Either you assure me right
now that amendment is out,

85
00:07:14,980 --> 00:07:17,973
or I am walking out that door and I
am gonna start launching missiles.

86
00:07:18,059 --> 00:07:20,494
The amendment was never
intended to stay in the bill.

87
00:07:20,578 --> 00:07:21,899
It's just there for leverage.
That's all.

88
00:07:21,980 --> 00:07:25,814
You threaten to cut federal funding
from union school districts?

89
00:07:25,899 --> 00:07:28,733
That's not a poker chip, Frank,
that's a goddamn dirty bomb.

90
00:07:28,819 --> 00:07:32,973
Look, the amendment
is not staying in the bill.

91
00:07:34,300 --> 00:07:37,259
I just need you to work with
me on performance standards.

92
00:07:37,619 --> 00:07:38,848
Performance standards?

93
00:07:39,778 --> 00:07:42,295
Are you fucking kidding me? You
agreed that they were already out.

94
00:07:42,420 --> 00:07:44,297
You can't just put it back in now, Frank.
Marty, look...

95
00:07:44,379 --> 00:07:46,177
I have a reputation
to uphold.

96
00:07:46,259 --> 00:07:49,650
I am the one that made the
union reps stay here for you

97
00:07:49,778 --> 00:07:52,249
while you're in Gaffney playing
with your fucking Peachoid.

98
00:07:52,338 --> 00:07:53,456
Marty...
You tell me right now,

99
00:07:53,540 --> 00:07:55,213
is that amendment
in or out?

100
00:07:56,059 --> 00:07:59,939
There is a middle ground here, Marty.
We just have to find it.

101
00:08:02,019 --> 00:08:03,932
I take that as a no.

102
00:08:06,939 --> 00:08:08,168
Okay.

103
00:08:10,300 --> 00:08:13,850
Marty, do not start a war
you know you're gonna lose.

104
00:08:13,939 --> 00:08:16,057
You fuck me,
I fuck back.

105
00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:22,249
Stamper!

106
00:08:22,338 --> 00:08:24,649
Marty and I have a good
working relationship.

107
00:08:24,739 --> 00:08:25,730
Or used to.

108
00:08:25,819 --> 00:08:26,970
You could see
he has a temper,

109
00:08:27,059 --> 00:08:29,211
but I can usually cut through
that and reason with him.

110
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:32,451
But I may have pushed him too far.
Which is worrisome.

111
00:08:32,538 --> 00:08:34,848
Friends make
the worst enemies.

112
00:08:37,019 --> 00:08:38,850
How'd it go?
What'd you hear?

113
00:08:38,978 --> 00:08:42,050
A lot of fucks. Well,
that pretty much says it.

114
00:08:42,658 --> 00:08:43,978
Let's think
this through...

115
00:08:44,058 --> 00:08:45,288
No, we've got the DNC
leadership meeting.

116
00:08:45,500 --> 00:08:46,726
What?

117
00:08:46,818 --> 00:08:49,207
I'd say you could skip it, but
Birch just dumped it on us.

118
00:08:49,378 --> 00:08:51,654
When? It's here. In 12 minutes.

119
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:53,413
Why here and not
the DNC headquarters?

120
00:08:53,538 --> 00:08:56,692
The DNC is doing renovations, they're
gonna be green-energy efficient.

121
00:08:56,778 --> 00:08:59,657
That's a charming
use of party funds.

122
00:09:00,098 --> 00:09:02,408
We've only been in this
space about three months.

123
00:09:02,858 --> 00:09:04,008
It's cool.

124
00:09:04,098 --> 00:09:05,976
Not exactly
<i>The Herald,</i> is it?

125
00:09:06,058 --> 00:09:08,653
Have you been to those offices?
Yes.

126
00:09:08,778 --> 00:09:10,928
Wrist-slitting
was in order.

127
00:09:11,338 --> 00:09:13,649
So, who else
is courting you?

128
00:09:14,178 --> 00:09:15,216
A few people.

129
00:09:15,338 --> 00:09:16,408
You mean everyone.

130
00:09:17,139 --> 00:09:18,777
There were a lot of
emails this morning...

131
00:09:18,858 --> 00:09:20,178
That's not surprising.

132
00:09:20,258 --> 00:09:22,726
You're having a moment,
people are interested.

133
00:09:22,818 --> 00:09:24,093
I'm one of them.

134
00:09:24,178 --> 00:09:26,851
But if eight minutes passes
on anything, I get bored.

135
00:09:26,978 --> 00:09:29,538
In eight minutes, I could be bored with you.
Unless you keep me interested.

136
00:09:30,938 --> 00:09:32,338
I think you can,

137
00:09:32,418 --> 00:09:33,774
and I think this
is the place for you

138
00:09:33,858 --> 00:09:36,009
to keep the rest of
the world interested, too.

139
00:09:36,418 --> 00:09:38,216
It's your call.
I won't chase you.

140
00:09:38,298 --> 00:09:39,652
I'm definitely tempted...

141
00:09:40,098 --> 00:09:42,055
Take as long as you
want to look around.

142
00:09:42,139 --> 00:09:45,097
Email me your figure. I'll
call you back with a counter.

143
00:09:49,740 --> 00:09:54,051
This is our top priority. Ohio,
Florida and Pennsylvania.

144
00:09:54,818 --> 00:09:57,128
We need all of them or
Walker's a one-term president.

145
00:09:57,218 --> 00:09:59,813
Pennsylvania is why he picked
Matthews as a running mate.

146
00:09:59,899 --> 00:10:01,730
But now we have to
find a replacement.

147
00:10:01,858 --> 00:10:03,656
The special election
is this November.

148
00:10:04,218 --> 00:10:06,370
Patricia Whittaker.
DNC chair.

149
00:10:06,538 --> 00:10:08,973
A rare example of someone
whose head is in the game

150
00:10:09,058 --> 00:10:10,856
instead of
up their backside.

151
00:10:10,938 --> 00:10:13,216
Competence is such an
exotic bird in these woods

152
00:10:13,378 --> 00:10:15,654
that I appreciate
it whenever I see it.

153
00:10:15,740 --> 00:10:17,808
Now, this also
affects the House.

154
00:10:17,899 --> 00:10:19,572
The new Governor will
oversee redistricting.

155
00:10:19,658 --> 00:10:20,853
We lose seats here,

156
00:10:20,938 --> 00:10:22,418
that means we could lose
our majority in Washington.

157
00:10:22,740 --> 00:10:25,697
Well, the RNC is backing Jack
Swofford, ex-mayor of Pittsburgh.

158
00:10:25,778 --> 00:10:27,895
He's got state-wide
name recognition

159
00:10:28,019 --> 00:10:29,338
and campaign machinery
in place...

160
00:10:29,418 --> 00:10:32,490
It's been three months
and we don't have dick.

161
00:10:32,577 --> 00:10:34,375
What about the A.G.?
Ben Pluckett?

162
00:10:34,500 --> 00:10:36,933
No, Ben's got his eyes set
on the Senate in '14.

163
00:10:37,019 --> 00:10:40,135
Yeah, which he'll lose because he
botched a sex offender sting last year.

164
00:10:40,218 --> 00:10:42,608
Well, there's always McHolland.
He's 78.

165
00:10:42,698 --> 00:10:44,928
When's the last time he held office?
When Carter was president?

166
00:10:45,019 --> 00:10:46,930
Reagan,
but same difference.

167
00:10:47,019 --> 00:10:49,055
Well, he has dignity.
He has gravitas.

168
00:10:49,139 --> 00:10:50,697
I mean, if you need someone
to fill Matthews' shoes...

169
00:10:50,778 --> 00:10:53,500
You can't fill Jim Matthews' shoes.
So we shouldn't even try.

170
00:10:53,938 --> 00:10:55,497
We need a fresh face.

171
00:10:55,577 --> 00:10:57,092
The state has
a weak bench.

172
00:10:57,178 --> 00:10:59,454
Well, let's go through all the
sitting Congressmen one by one,

173
00:10:59,577 --> 00:11:00,899
and see if anybody
sticks out from the crowd.

174
00:11:01,019 --> 00:11:03,851
All right. I got the list right here.
Okay. Go ahead.

175
00:11:03,938 --> 00:11:06,577
Pennsylvania's first
district, Peter Russo.

176
00:11:06,658 --> 00:11:09,492
Cross him off. He's no good.
No experience. No chops.

177
00:11:09,577 --> 00:11:12,538
Okay, moving on. Second
district, Gwendolyn Pierce.

178
00:11:12,620 --> 00:11:15,577
Gwen's too controversial.
Very vocal on abortion...

179
00:11:15,658 --> 00:11:16,649
And, Caroline?

180
00:11:16,818 --> 00:11:17,854
She's good.

181
00:11:17,978 --> 00:11:18,968
Yeah? How're the boys?

182
00:11:19,139 --> 00:11:20,128
All fuckin'
four of them?

183
00:11:20,218 --> 00:11:21,971
You feed 'em.

184
00:11:22,058 --> 00:11:24,370
You got any pictures?
On your phone?

185
00:11:24,457 --> 00:11:26,575
Come on. Let's cut the
shit, Pete, will ya?

186
00:11:26,698 --> 00:11:28,817
What are we gonna do
about the shipyard?

187
00:11:32,139 --> 00:11:35,130
BRAC had their hearing.
They slated it for closing.

188
00:11:35,218 --> 00:11:37,414
Yeah, and why
didn't you testify?

189
00:11:37,538 --> 00:11:39,734
We're talking
12,000 jobs here.

190
00:11:39,818 --> 00:11:42,378
My hands were tied, Paul.
People wanted it closed.

191
00:11:42,500 --> 00:11:44,250
I was under a lot of pressure.
From who?

192
00:11:45,218 --> 00:11:47,335
People high up the food chain.
There's nothing I could do.

193
00:11:47,778 --> 00:11:51,055
That's bullshit. You go back to BRAC.
You talk to the DOD.

194
00:11:51,139 --> 00:11:53,495
You talk to the Secretary of the Navy.
You do something...

195
00:11:53,577 --> 00:11:54,568
It's not gonna happen.

196
00:11:54,698 --> 00:11:55,734
Okay, why not?

197
00:11:56,098 --> 00:11:57,452
I told you,
it's political.

198
00:11:57,538 --> 00:11:59,575
Okay, so I'm supposed to go back
to the Shipbuilder's Association

199
00:11:59,658 --> 00:12:00,933
and say what now,
exactly?

200
00:12:01,298 --> 00:12:03,938
That they're out of work because
Pete Russo's playing politics?

201
00:12:06,258 --> 00:12:07,487
I mean, Jesus, Pete.

202
00:12:07,938 --> 00:12:10,692
We're the ones who got you fuckin'
elected in the first place.

203
00:12:11,818 --> 00:12:14,207
Now you're gonna
turn your back on us?

204
00:12:14,298 --> 00:12:16,096
You should go.

205
00:12:18,178 --> 00:12:19,407
Seriously?

206
00:12:21,778 --> 00:12:23,817
I just got here.
You're kickin' me out now?

207
00:12:24,978 --> 00:12:27,698
Hey, I'm fuckin'
talkin' to you.

208
00:12:30,139 --> 00:12:31,856
I thought we
grew up together.

209
00:12:31,978 --> 00:12:35,528
But this guy, sitting
behind his big desk,

210
00:12:36,258 --> 00:12:39,217
I don't even know
who the fuck he is.

211
00:12:40,500 --> 00:12:42,173
Where's the Pete Russo who
knew how to throw a punch

212
00:12:42,258 --> 00:12:44,774
when his back was
against the wall?

213
00:12:44,978 --> 00:12:46,935
That guy was my friend.

214
00:12:59,620 --> 00:13:01,654
Every teacher in the country?
A month before school ends?

215
00:13:01,740 --> 00:13:02,774
He doesn't need
all of them.

216
00:13:02,858 --> 00:13:04,850
Fifteen, 20 states.
That's all.

217
00:13:04,938 --> 00:13:06,975
But the AFT and the NEA
can't agree on anything.

218
00:13:07,058 --> 00:13:09,096
You underestimate
Marty Spinella.

219
00:13:10,899 --> 00:13:12,252
So which one
do we target?

220
00:13:13,978 --> 00:13:15,207
We have a better
chance with the NEA.

221
00:13:15,978 --> 00:13:17,413
You think Chuck Sloan
will bite?

222
00:13:17,500 --> 00:13:20,649
Cooperate, we give your people
protection and a place at the banquet.

223
00:13:20,740 --> 00:13:22,457
Fight us, we break you.

224
00:13:22,577 --> 00:13:24,173
He'll bite.
Get him on the phone.

225
00:13:24,258 --> 00:13:25,294
It's after 2:00.

226
00:13:26,058 --> 00:13:28,698
Spinella's potentially mobilizing
the largest teachers' strike

227
00:13:28,778 --> 00:13:31,053
in United States history.
Nobody's sleeping.

228
00:13:31,139 --> 00:13:33,096
I'll call him
right now.

229
00:13:34,098 --> 00:13:35,851
I'm sorry.
Are we being too loud?

230
00:13:35,938 --> 00:13:37,293
A little.

231
00:13:40,019 --> 00:13:41,053
What are you working on?

232
00:13:41,139 --> 00:13:43,289
The gala.
There's so much to do.

233
00:13:45,098 --> 00:13:46,134
Did Nancy
send you my list?

234
00:13:46,298 --> 00:13:47,370
She did.

235
00:13:47,457 --> 00:13:49,211
And what'd you think?

236
00:13:49,577 --> 00:13:52,491
It's a good list.
Thanks for inviting them.

237
00:13:55,298 --> 00:13:56,778
Is something wrong?

238
00:13:59,218 --> 00:14:01,938
It's still not anywhere near
what Remy brought to the table.

239
00:14:03,500 --> 00:14:05,729
SanCorp offered
1.5 million, Francis.

240
00:14:05,818 --> 00:14:09,370
I'm adding up the numbers and
we're only at half a million.

241
00:14:09,457 --> 00:14:11,575
I got Chuck on the phone.
In a minute.

242
00:14:11,658 --> 00:14:12,694
I can make
more calls...

243
00:14:12,778 --> 00:14:14,132
Enough to raise
1.5 million?

244
